                              13          4           30.8          \u001b[4m1\u001b[24m949\n\u001b[90m20\u001b[39m The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring          13          4           30.8          \u001b[4m2\u001b[24m002\n","output_type":"stream"}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"With the ajustment - The winners with the most nominations are:\n\nTitanic (Because apparently, even a three-hour movie couldn't outlast their Oscar acceptance speeches)\n\nAll About Eve (Talk about a masterclass in campaigning. We're pretty sure they invented the \"For Your Consideration\" ad)\n\nLa La Land (They might not have gotten that ending they dreamed of, but hey, at least they got a bunch of trophies!)\n\nAs for the 2024 Oscars - Oppenheimer is now on the list. Tied together with \"Gone with Wind\" and others  with 13 nominations.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"top_movies <- oscars %>%\n  group_by(film, year_film) %>%\n  summarise(\n    nominations = n(),\n    oscars_won = sum(as.logical(winner)),\n    percentage_won = round(sum(oscars_won) / nominations * 100, 1),\n    year_ceremony = first(year_ceremony),  \n    .groups = 'drop'\n  ) %>%\n  filter(film != \"\") %>%\n  arrange(desc(nominations), desc(oscars_won)) %>%\n  head(n = 20)\noptions(width = 150, dplyr.print_max = Inf)\nprint(top_movies)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-03-17T17:02:31.729087Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-03-17T17:02:31.730798Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-03-17T17:02:32.08893Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The Mount Rushmore of Oscar Hoarders (with a staggering 11 awards each):\n\nTitanic (Because apparently, an iceberg couldn't sink this movie's awards haul)\nBen-Hur (A historical epic that truly deserves a whole chariot full of golden statues)\nThe Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King (The One Award to Rule Them All)\n\nAgain with the Oscars 2024 Oppenheimer is also on the list of movies with the most Oscars won - seven in fact. The same as movies as \"Shakespeare in love\" and \"Schindlers list\".","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"library(dplyr)\noptions(width = 200, dplyr.print_max = Inf)\n\ntop_movies_wins <- oscars %>%\n  group_by(film, year_film) %>%\n  summarise(\n    nominations = n(),\n    oscars_won = sum(as.logical(winner)),\n    percentage_won = round(sum(oscars_won) / nominations * 100, 1),\n    year_ceremony = first(year_ceremony),  \n    .groups = 'drop'\n  ) %>%\n  filter(film != \"\") %>%\n  arrange(desc(oscars_won), desc(nominations)) %>%\n  head(n = 20)\n\nprint(top_movies_wins)\n\n","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-03-17T17:02:49.642658Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-03-17T17:02:49.644267Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-03-17T17:02:49.9923Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"There are, of course, a select few cinematic deities who casually stroll through award season, scooping up every golden statue in sight. Talk about showing off.\n\nExhibit A: The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King (Because apparently, one does not simply lose an Oscar)","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"library(dplyr)\noptions(width = 200, dplyr.print_max = Inf)\n\ntop_movies_win_percentage <- oscars %>%\n  group_by(film, year_film) %>%\n  summarise(\n    nominations = n(),\n    oscars_won = sum(as.logical(winner)),\n    percentage_won = round(sum(oscars_won) / nominations * 100, 1),\n    year_film = first(year_film), \n    year_ceremony = first(year_ceremony),  \n    .groups = 'drop'\n  ) %>%\n  filter(film != \"\") %>%\n  arrange(desc(percentage_won), desc(nominations)) %>%\n  head(n = 20)\n\nprint(top_movies_win_percentage)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-03-17T17:10:17.783514Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-03-17T17:10:17.785332Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-03-17T17:10:18.260921Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Movies with the most nominations per year. The dataset has 319 empty cells in the film categorie. They are excluded from the code.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Most nominations per year and film\nlibrary(dplyr)\noptions(width = 200, dplyr.print_max = Inf)\n\nmost_nominations <- oscars %>%\n  filter(!is.na(film) & film != \"\") %>%  # Exclude rows where the 'film' column is NA or empty\n  group_by(year_ceremony, film) %>% \n  summarise(num_nominations = n()) %>%\n  group_by(year_ceremony) %>%  \n  mutate(max_nominations = max(num_nominations)) %>%\n  filter(num_nominations == max_nominations) %>%\n  arrange(year_ceremony, desc(num_nominations)) %>%\n  ungroup()\n\n# Print the result\nprint(most_nominations)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-03-18T18:08:46.675691Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-03-18T18:08:46.690218Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-03-18T18:08:46.91075Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":9,"outputs":[{"name":"stderr","text":"\u001b[1m\u001b[22m`summarise()` has grouped output by 'year_ceremony'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.\n","output_type":"stream"},{"name":"stdout","text":"\u001b[90m# A tibble: 129 × 4\u001b[39m\n    year_ceremony film                                              num_nominations max_nominations\n            \u001b[3m\u001b[90m<int>\u001b[39m\u001b[23m \u001b[3m\u001b[90m<chr>\u001b[39m\u001b[23m                                                       \u001b[3m\u001b[90m<int>\u001b[39m\u001b[23m           \u001b[3m\u001b[90m<int>\u001b[39m\u001b[23m\n\u001b[90m  1\u001b[39m          \u001b[4m1\u001b[24m928 7th Heaven                                                      5               5\n\u001b[90m  2\u001b[39m          \u001b[4m1\u001b[24m929 The Patriot                                                     5               5\n\u001b[90m  3\u001b[39m          \u001b[4m1\u001b[24m930 The Love Parade                                                 5               5\n\u0